# =====================================================
# .env.local.example - Safe Environment Variables Only
# =====================================================
# Copy this file to .env.local and fill in your values
# This file contains ONLY public/client-safe variables
# =====================================================

# Firebase Configuration (Public - Safe for client-side)
# Get these from your Firebase Console > Project Settings
REACT_APP_FIREBASE_API_KEY=your-firebase-api-key-here
REACT_APP_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN=your-project.firebaseapp.com
REACT_APP_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=your-project-id
REACT_APP_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET=your-project.appspot.com
REACT_APP_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID=your-sender-id
REACT_APP_FIREBASE_APP_ID=your-app-id

# Public Application Configuration
REACT_APP_SENDGRID_FROM_EMAIL=sage@sagerock.com
REACT_APP_URL=https://sagerock.com
# =====================================================
# IMPORTANT SECURITY NOTES:
# =====================================================
#
# NEVER put these in .env.local or any REACT_APP_* variable:
# ❌ OpenAI API Keys (sk-proj-...)
# ❌ Anthropic API Keys (sk-ant-...)
# ❌ Google AI API Keys
# ❌ Perplexity API Keys
# ❌ SendGrid API Keys (SG....)
# ❌ Any service account keys
# ❌ Any secret/private keys
#
# These should ONLY be in:
# 1. Vercel Environment Variables (server-side)
# 2. API routes/Edge functions
# 3. Never in client-side code
#
# =====================================================
# LOCAL DEVELOPMENT ONLY:
# =====================================================
#
# For local development with API keys, you have options:
#
# Option 1: Keep keys in .env.local temporarily for local testing
#           BUT remove them before deploying
#
# Option 2: Use Vercel CLI (`vercel dev`) to run locally with
#           server-side environment variables
#
# Option 3: Create local API proxy routes that mirror production
#
# =====================================================